Task 1.a

In this part, bet-at-home, bwin, youwin, bet365 and Tipico was selected as 5 bookmakers to analyze their odds. First of all, their odds for different odd types were combined in a particular data. Final odds of each bookmaker were taken into consideration.Then the combined odd data was merged with the matches data. After all, PCA were implemented on this combined data.

Figure 2a: PCA for Combined Data

As mentioned before by observing the importance of the components, the most crucial components are component 1, component 2 and component 3 since they can form the huge part of the variation. It will be useful for a predictor to use first three components to explain the model if there is a restriction about the number of components to be used.

Figure 2b: PCA for Combined Data with IsOver

In order to see the relationship between match results (over 2.5 or under 2.5) with the odds of different bookmakers (5 of them) PCA analysis was applied and the first two components were plotted. As it can be seen from the figure, matches finished over 2.5 are shown with red points while the matches resulted under 2.5 are shown with black ones. According to the graph, it can be confidently said that the points are not linearly seperabe (black and red points), which means that whether the matches will result over 2.5 (or under 2.5) cannot be explained clearly by the odds data. However, this plot is in two dimension and first two components were used. The first two components explain the 70% of the total variation. It may be useful to see the plot first 26 components (they explain the 99% of the variation), which requires 26 dimensions and it is not realistic to plot such a graph.

## Cumulative Var  0.111  0.222  0.333  0.444  0.556  0.667  0.778  0.889
##                Comp.9
## SS loadings     1.000
## Proportion Var  0.111
## Cumulative Var  1.000

Figure 17: Loadings (Eigenvectors)

After implementing PCA to the patches, it can be said that the most important component is the first one. it can explain huge amount of variance itself (91% of the total variance). Since the first component can explain nearly the total variation and the loadings of the component 1 are close to each other, tle plot of this component (scores) will give a very reasonable image.

4.b

In this part, the first, second and third component was used seperately to reconstruct the image. After these three components were used for patches, the scores (recall that each patch is extracted from a certain location so that you can obtain an image from the scores). of these three components were plotted on a single plot after scaling (since the values must be between 0 and 1 as mentioned before) as can be seen from the figure 18.

Figure 18: Images constructed by the scores of Component 1,2 and 3, respectively on the figure

4.c

Components (eigenvectors) themselves refers to a patch. Therefore, if we transform the components into a matrix form, we can obtain an image. In this part the component 1,2 and 3 were transformed into 3 by 3 matrices. Then they were scaled to the interval from 0 to 1 because the values must be between 0 to 1 so as mentioned before. Finally they were plotted on a single graph as it can be seen from the figure 19.

Figure 19: Component 1,2 and 3 (as 3 by 3 image), respectively on the figure

After plotting the first 3 components, it can be said that different eigenvectors are identifying different level of intensities. For example the first component differs on the middle on the image while second ones intensity level is changing in the vertical azis and the third one has different level of intensities in the horizontal axis.
